{
	"nodes":[
		{"id":"80925c1402773175","type":"text","text":"# Gradient Descent Update Step\n\nThis is the core learning rule behind neural networks.\n\nThe model has parameters:\n\n```python\nx\n```\n\nThese parameters could be:\n\n* weights\n* biases\n* embeddings\n* anything trainable\n\nThe goal is to adjust them so the loss becomes smaller.\n\n---\n\n# The Formula\n\nx_{new}=x_{old}-\\left(\\eta \\cdot \\nabla f(x)\\right)\n\nWhere:\n\n| Symbol        | Meaning                 |\n| ------------- | ----------------------- |\n| (x)           | parameter/weight        |\n| (\\eta)        | learning rate           |\n| (\\nabla f(x)) | gradient                |\n| `-`           | move opposite the slope |\n\n---\n\n# Intuition\n\nImagine standing on a mountain blindfolded.\n\nYou want to reach the bottom.\n\nThe gradient tells you:\n\n> \"The steepest uphill direction is this way.\"\n\nTo go DOWN:\n\nyou move in the opposite direction.\n\nThat is why:\n\n```python\nx = x - lr * grad\n```\n\n---\n\n# What the Gradient Actually Is\n\nThe gradient is:\n\n[\n\\frac{d(\\text{loss})}{dx}\n]\n\nMeaning:\n\n> \"How much does the loss change if x changes slightly?\"\n\n---\n\nExample:\n\n```python\ngrad = 5\n```\n\nmeans:\n\n> Increasing `x` increases loss strongly.\n\nSo we should decrease `x`.\n\nThus:\n\n```python\nx = x - lr * 5\n```\n\n---\n\n# Learning Rate\n\nThe learning rate controls step size.\n\nSmall learning rate:\n\n```python\nlr = 0.0001\n```\n\n* stable\n* slow\n\nLarge learning rate:\n\n```python\nlr = 1.0\n```\n\n* fast\n* may overshoot or explode\n\n---\n\n# Concrete Example\n\nSuppose:\n\n```python\nx = 10\ngrad = 2\nlr = 0.1\n```\n\nUpdate:\n\n```python\nx = 10 - (0.1 * 2)\nx = 9.8\n```\n\nWe moved slightly toward a better value.\n\n---\n\n# Where Gradients Come From\n\nPyTorch computes gradients using:\n\n```python\nloss.backward()\n```\n\nThis uses:\n\n* computational graphs\n* chain rule\n* automatic differentiation (autograd)\n\nAfter backward:\n\n```python\nparameter.grad\n```\n\ncontains the gradient.\n\n---\n\n# Full Training Loop\n\nTypical PyTorch loop:\n\n```python\nfor batch in data:\n\n    optimizer.zero_grad()\n\n    predictions = model(batch)\n\n    loss = criterion(predictions, targets)\n\n    loss.backward()\n\n    optimizer.step()\n```\n\n---\n\n# `optimizer.step()`\n\nThis performs:\n\n```python\nx = x - lr * grad\n```\n\nfor every trainable parameter.\n\n---\n\n# Why `zero_grad()` Is Crucial\n\nThis part confuses many beginners because PyTorch behaves differently from what people expect.\n\nPyTorch ACCUMULATES gradients by default.\n\nMeaning:\n\n```python\nloss.backward()\n```\n\ndoes NOT replace gradients.\n\nIt ADDS to existing gradients.\n\n---\n\n# What Accumulation Means\n\nSuppose:\n\nFirst iteration:\n\n```python\nw.grad = 3\n```\n\nSecond iteration:\n\n```python\nw.grad += 5\n```\n\nNow:\n\n```python\nw.grad = 8\n```\n\nNOT `5`.\n\n---\n\n# Why PyTorch Does This\n\nBecause gradient accumulation is sometimes useful.\n\nExample:\n\n* huge models\n* GPU memory limits\n* simulate larger batch sizes\n\nPeople intentionally accumulate gradients across multiple mini-batches.\n\n---\n\n# But Normally You DON'T Want This\n\nIn standard training:\n\neach batch should compute fresh gradients.\n\nSo before every backward pass:\n\n```python\noptimizer.zero_grad()\n```\n\nresets gradients.\n\n---\n\n# Without `zero_grad()`\n\nYou accidentally get:\n\n```text\nnew_gradient = old_gradient + current_gradient\n```\n\nThe model updates become mathematically incorrect.\n\nTraining becomes unstable or completely broken.\n\n---\n\n# Visual Example\n\nIteration 1:\n\n```python\ngrad = 2\n```\n\nIteration 2 actual gradient:\n\n```python\ngrad = 3\n```\n\nWithout zeroing:\n\n```python\nstored_grad = 2 + 3 = 5\n```\n\nNow optimizer uses `5`.\n\nThat update is wrong.\n\n---\n\n# Correct Order\n\nThe standard order is:\n\n```python\noptimizer.zero_grad()\n\nloss.backward()\n\noptimizer.step()\n```\n\n---\n\n# Why Zero BEFORE Backward\n\nBecause:\n\n```python\nbackward()\n```\n\nadds gradients into `.grad`.\n\nYou want `.grad` empty before accumulation starts.\n\n---\n\n# Internal Mental Model\n\nThink of `.grad` as a bucket.\n\n`backward()` pours gradient values into the bucket.\n\n`zero_grad()` empties the bucket.\n\nIf you never empty it:\n\nthe bucket keeps filling forever.\n\n---\n","x":-980,"y":-500,"width":1105,"height":530},
		{"id":"87fe75373c1dcfee","type":"text","text":"**Gradient Iteration Example**\nWatch how gradients accumulate if you forget `zero_grad()`:\n\n```python\n# --- Iteration 1 ---\noptimizer.zero_grad()\nloss = (w * x1).sum()\nloss.backward()      # w.grad = 2.0\noptimizer.step()     # w updated with 2.0 ✓\n\n# --- Iteration 2 (CORRECT) ---\noptimizer.zero_grad() # w.grad reset to 0\nloss = (w * x2).sum()\nloss.backward()       # w.grad = 3.0\noptimizer.step()      # uses 3.0 ✓\n\n# --- Iteration 2 (WRONG, no zero_grad) ---\n# w.grad still has 2.0 from iter 1\nloss.backward()       # w.grad = 2.0 + 3.0 = 5.0\noptimizer.step()      # uses 5.0 ✗ WRONG!\n```","x":-680,"y":133,"width":500,"height":320},
		{"id":"f2c838e457de8cbb","type":"text","text":"1. **Update Step:** We adjust x to move closer to the minimum: xnew=xold−(Learning_Rate×Gradient).\n2. **Zero Grad (`zero_grad()`):** _Crucial step._ PyTorch accumulates gradients by default. If you don't reset them to zero at the end of a loop, the math will be completely wrong on the next step.","x":-672,"y":-820,"width":490,"height":140},
		{"id":"98ad8a49b8b9a800","type":"text","text":"**Batch**\nA small subset of the full dataset processed together in one forward pass. Instead of feeding all 60k images at once, you feed e.g. 32 at a time.\n\n```python\nfor batch in DataLoader(dataset, batch_size=32):\n    # batch.shape → (32, features)\n```\n\n*Smaller batches = less memory, noisier gradients.\nLarger batches = more memory, smoother gradients.*","x":-2140,"y":-880,"width":500,"height":418},
		{"id":"34bf4c2b04659976","type":"text","text":"**Criterion (Loss Function)**\nMeasures how wrong the model's predictions are. The optimizer's job is to minimize this number.\n\n```python\n# Classification → CrossEntropy\ncriterion = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()\n# Regression → MSE\ncriterion = nn.MSELoss()\n\nloss = criterion(predictions, targets)\n```\n\n*Lower loss = better model.*","x":-2140,"y":-408,"width":500,"height":409},
		{"id":"4c12cbe3b91a5ff9","type":"text","text":"**`DataLoader`**\nWraps a `Dataset` and serves it in batches. Handles shuffling, parallel loading, and batching automatically.\n\n```python\nfrom torch.utils.data import DataLoader, TensorDataset\n\ndataset = TensorDataset(X, y)\nloader = DataLoader(\n    dataset,\n    batch_size=32,   # samples per batch\n    shuffle=True,    # randomize order each epoch\n    num_workers=4    # parallel data loading\n)\n\nfor batch_X, batch_y in loader:\n    # batch_X.shape → (32, features)\n    pass\n```\n\n**Key params:**\n- `batch_size`: how many samples per step\n- `shuffle`: randomize to prevent memorizing order\n- `num_workers`: CPU threads for loading\n- `drop_last`: drop incomplete final batch","x":-2780,"y":-1060,"width":520,"height":400},
		{"id":"94659e204d6316dc","type":"text","text":"**Custom Loss Function**\nYes! Subclass `nn.Module` and define `forward()`. Must return a **scalar** tensor so `.backward()` works.\n\n```python\nclass MyCustomLoss(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, penalty_weight=0.5):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.penalty_weight = penalty_weight\n\n    def forward(self, pred, target):\n        mse = ((pred - target) ** 2).mean()\n        # Add custom penalty: punish large predictions\n        penalty = (pred ** 2).mean()\n        return mse + self.penalty_weight * penalty\n```\n\n**Usage** (same as built-in):\n```python\ncriterion = MyCustomLoss(penalty_weight=0.1)\nloss = criterion(predictions, targets)\nloss.backward()  # works!\n```\n\n**Rules:**\n- Use only PyTorch ops (so autograd can track them)\n- Return a single scalar\n- Don't use `.item()` or `.detach()` on the result","x":-2780,"y":-620,"width":520,"height":460},
		{"id":"45362f778fcdf2c7","type":"text","text":"**`loss.backward()`**\nWalks backward through the computation graph and computes the gradient of the loss w.r.t. every parameter that has `requires_grad=True`.\n\n```python\nloss = criterion(pred, target)\nloss.backward()  # fills .grad for all params\n```\n\n*Uses the chain rule (autograd) under the hood.*","x":-2140,"y":55,"width":500,"height":297},
		{"id":"1c07536db3f5a010","type":"text","text":"**`parameter.grad`**\nAfter `backward()`, every trainable tensor stores its gradient in `.grad`.\n\n```python\nw = torch.tensor([3.0], requires_grad=True)\nloss = (w * 2).sum()\nloss.backward()\nprint(w.grad)  # tensor([2.])\n```\n\n*It tells the optimizer which direction & how much to nudge each weight.*","x":-2140,"y":406,"width":500,"height":351},
		{"id":"ae21e1c40ba83fe8","type":"text","text":"**`optimizer.zero_grad()`**\nResets all `.grad` attributes to zero. Must be called **before** `backward()` each iteration, because PyTorch **accumulates** gradients by default.\n\n```python\noptimizer.zero_grad()   # empty the bucket\nloss.backward()         # fill with fresh grads\noptimizer.step()        # update weights\n```\n\n*Forgetting this → stale gradients pile up → wrong updates.*","x":-2140,"y":810,"width":500,"height":270}
	],
